The symmetric difference of two sets A and B, denoted as A Δ B, is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection. In other words, it is the union of the sets minus their intersection.

A Δ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

First, let's find the union of A and B (A ∪ B):

A ∪ B = {1, 3, 5, 7} ∪ {3, 6, 9} = {1, 3, 5, 7, 6, 9}

Next, let's find the intersection of A and B (A ∩ B):

A ∩ B = {1, 3, 5, 7} ∩ {3, 6, 9} = {3}

Now, we can find the symmetric difference of A and B (A Δ B):

A Δ B = {1, 3, 5, 7, 6, 9} - {3} = {1, 5, 7, 6, 9}

Now let's show that the symmetric difference is commutative. This means that A Δ B = B Δ A.

B Δ A = (B ∪ A) - (B ∩ A)

The union and intersection of sets are commutative, so:

B ∪ A = A ∪ B = {1, 3, 5, 7, 6, 9}
B ∩ A = A ∩ B = {3}

Now we can find the symmetric difference of B and A (B Δ A):

B Δ A = {1, 3, 5, 7, 6, 9} - {3} = {1, 5, 7, 6, 9}

As we can see, A Δ B = {1, 5, 7, 6, 9} and B Δ A = {1, 5, 7, 6, 9}, which means the symmetric difference is commutative.
